<font color="#FF0000">CAMARADERIE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Jan 16 13:59:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To All Concerned,<br>
If I may, I would like to try to steer this dialog from myths in the media, etc., to myths among veterans.  My limited exposure with veterans since I returned from Nam has been them trying to convince me of this great over encompassing camaraderie that was suppose to have existed, especially within the bush units.  Also, these myths of, WE TAKE CARE OF OUR OWN and, my favorite, WE NEVER LEFT ANYONE IN THE BUSH.  In my own experiences, I found this not to have existed or the case.  It is possible that this may have been due to the fact that I was a combat medic instead of a grunt, I don't know.<br><br>
The only way I will find out is putting my shit and perceptions out to you guys out there.<br><br>
Differences between this medic and grunts I have met.  I am always impressed when I hear a vet rattle off the names of the guys in his unit, those that died and those that survived.  For me, I remember no names nor faces, but I remember the wounds.  My one and only photo was taken of my platoon one Christmas morning.  Many a year, I have stared at that photo trying to remember those in it, but the only face I recognize is mine.<br><br>
It was brought to my attention by a vet counselor(squad leader-Ashau Valley, 66-68) about the divide between medics and others.  He stated that medics were viewed as garbagemen, that we were there only to pick up the garbage (dead/wounded), pull out the plastic bags (body bags), and thrown the garbage onto the truck (medivacs).  At the time, I told him, bullshit.<br><br>
Some of my experiences- During one ops, we were inserted in a area for whatever reason, and humped for about an hour when we ran into an ambush.  Five of the point team went down, four KIA, one wounded.  While working on the wounded individual, my platoon pulled back and was extricated from the area.  It was the next day that they came back to collect the &quot;dead&quot;, to find me waiting, the KIA's readied and strapped to makeshift litters.  The only acknowledgement that We were left behind was a c-rat pack of smokes, matches and a canteen of water.<br><br>
One log day, I recieved my resupplies which included a glass bottle of methyolate(red stuff).  Later, we were rushing to get to an area we were to be.  While we ran, the bottle broke, contaminating much of my supplies.  I called up to the L.T. and asked to stop so I could salvage what I could. When I emptied my ruck and and had everything spread out, the L.T. told everyone to pick it up and to move out.  I called him back and told him my situation.  His response was that I could catch up with them later.  I had two choices, the first being that to throw everything back in the rucksac and lose everything, or to finish the cleanup and salvage what I could.  I chose the latter. I can still see myself on my kness working as the column was passing me by.  When I looked up, all eyes were diverted from me.  I remember when I lost sight of the last man in the column.  I eventually finished and it took me only about a half an hour to catch up, but it was a long half hour.<br><br>
Are my experiences unique?  I don't know.  That's why I want to hear from others.  Are these kinds of experiences unique to medics. Don't know, never talked to a medic on this level even if I knew of any.<br><br>
I suspect that other medics experienced the same as I, feel the same as I, differing only in a matter of degree.<br><br>
So, fellow medics and grunts.  Call me on my shit, tell me I am full of it.  Tell me that my impressions of these myths are wrong, I truely wish that were the case.<br><br>
While I have the soapbox, thanks to Arthur, Mike and RN Dusty, for letting me bend their ear.<br>

<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


